[ Silence ]

00:00:11.445 --> 00:00:12.145 align:middle line:90%


00:00:12.145 --> 00:00:13.346 align:middle line:90%
>> [Background Music]

00:00:13.346 --> 00:00:14.114 align:middle line:84%
>> And I think many people
today don't know what

00:00:14.114 --> 00:00:15.248 align:middle line:90%
to believe anymore.

00:00:15.248 --> 00:00:17.751 align:middle line:84%
>> People are basically
going to keep on them

00:00:17.751 --> 00:00:19.653 align:middle line:84%
to help uncover what
really happened.

00:00:19.653 --> 00:00:22.022 align:middle line:84%
>> I felt like something
was watching me.

00:00:22.022 --> 00:00:23.256 align:middle line:84%
>> We weren't given
all the information.

00:00:23.256 --> 00:00:25.725 align:middle line:84%
We weren't told the
entire story.

00:00:25.725 --> 00:00:32.999 align:middle line:90%
[ Music ]

00:00:32.999 --> 00:00:34.334 align:middle line:90%
>> And now the host

00:00:34.334 --> 00:00:37.204 align:middle line:84%
of the nationally syndicated,
Coast to Coast A.M.

00:00:37.204 --> 00:00:39.840 align:middle line:84%
[applause] and  Guy MTV
bring you  Beyond Belief

00:00:39.840 --> 00:00:41.141 align:middle line:90%
with George Noory.

00:00:41.141 --> 00:00:42.609 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: Well,
welcome to  Beyond Belief .

00:00:42.609 --> 00:00:46.213 align:middle line:84%
When I was younger one of my
boyhood idols was Rod Serling,

00:00:46.213 --> 00:00:48.081 align:middle line:84%
the creator of  The
Twilight Zone .

00:00:48.081 --> 00:00:52.986 align:middle line:84%
I loved those episodes; I was
obsessed with the things he did.

00:00:52.986 --> 00:00:56.289 align:middle line:84%
Little did I know that later
on in life I would get a chance

00:00:56.289 --> 00:01:00.794 align:middle line:84%
and an opportunity to know his
wife Carol, his daughter Anne,

00:01:00.794 --> 00:01:03.029 align:middle line:84%
and our next guest
on  Beyond Belief .

00:01:03.029 --> 00:01:06.099 align:middle line:84%
He's a Hollywood writer,
producer, director,

00:01:06.099 --> 00:01:09.569 align:middle line:84%
and author of  The Twilight
Zone Companion , Marc Zicree.

00:01:09.569 --> 00:01:11.271 align:middle line:90%
Marc [applause]!

00:01:11.271 --> 00:01:12.539 align:middle line:90%
Whoo!

00:01:12.539 --> 00:01:13.473 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Hi, George.

00:01:13.473 --> 00:01:14.274 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
Always a pleasure.

00:01:14.274 --> 00:01:14.975 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Oh, my God.

00:01:14.975 --> 00:01:15.842 align:middle line:90%
It's so good to see you.

00:01:15.842 --> 00:01:16.375 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
Good to see you.

00:01:16.375 --> 00:01:17.210 align:middle line:90%
Have a seat.

00:01:17.210 --> 00:01:17.911 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yeah, thank you.

00:01:17.911 --> 00:01:18.912 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: You are

00:01:18.912 --> 00:01:21.314 align:middle line:84%
such a genius [laughter]
at what you do.

00:01:21.314 --> 00:01:22.816 align:middle line:90%
I mean, truly remarkable.

00:01:22.816 --> 00:01:24.017 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: Yeah,
well thanks, George.

00:01:24.017 --> 00:01:25.118 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: And it's
always good to see you.

00:01:25.118 --> 00:01:26.553 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: It's
always great to be here.

00:01:26.553 --> 00:01:28.220 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: Marc also took
The Twilight Zone  episodes

00:01:28.220 --> 00:01:30.190 align:middle line:90%
and put them in a whole DVD set.

00:01:30.190 --> 00:01:30.657 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yeah, yeah.

00:01:30.657 --> 00:01:31.725 align:middle line:90%
We did.

00:01:31.725 --> 00:01:33.059 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: And
it worked out great.

00:01:33.059 --> 00:01:34.194 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: We did the
DVDs and the Blu-Rays, and you

00:01:34.194 --> 00:01:35.295 align:middle line:84%
and I got to do audio
commentaries on the --

00:01:35.295 --> 00:01:36.263 align:middle line:84%
on our favorite  Twilight
Zone  episodes.

00:01:36.263 --> 00:01:37.196 align:middle line:90%
What a fun time that was.

00:01:37.196 --> 00:01:37.898 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: It was.

00:01:37.898 --> 00:01:39.266 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yeah.

00:01:39.266 --> 00:01:40.033 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: How did you
get interested, first of all,

00:01:40.033 --> 00:01:40.734 align:middle line:90%
in  The Twilight Zone ?

00:01:40.734 --> 00:01:42.135 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Sure.

00:01:42.135 --> 00:01:44.638 align:middle line:84%
Well, you know when I was a kid
I -- it was on past my bedtime,

00:01:44.638 --> 00:01:46.940 align:middle line:84%
and then one day my stepfather
was tinkering in the garage,

00:01:46.940 --> 00:01:48.175 align:middle line:84%
and there was an
old TV set there.

00:01:48.175 --> 00:01:50.377 align:middle line:84%
And he actually had one
TV that just got sound,

00:01:50.377 --> 00:01:51.945 align:middle line:84%
and one TV that just got
picture, and they were

00:01:51.945 --> 00:01:53.313 align:middle line:84%
on [laughter] different
channels,

00:01:53.313 --> 00:01:55.782 align:middle line:84%
and on the picture one there
was this flying saucer landing

00:01:55.782 --> 00:01:57.851 align:middle line:84%
and this weird thing with
these -- these astronauts.

00:01:57.851 --> 00:01:59.553 align:middle line:84%
It was an episode
called "Death Ship,"

00:01:59.553 --> 00:02:01.288 align:middle line:84%
and it was the first episode
of  Twilight Zone  I ever saw,

00:02:01.288 --> 00:02:02.956 align:middle line:90%
one of the hour-long episodes.

00:02:02.956 --> 00:02:04.524 align:middle line:90%
And -- and I was hooked.

00:02:04.524 --> 00:02:05.892 align:middle line:90%
I was hooked.

00:02:05.892 --> 00:02:08.094 align:middle line:84%
And as soon as I got out of
college I decided I was going

00:02:08.094 --> 00:02:10.063 align:middle line:84%
to write a book about  The
Twilight Zone  and learn how --

00:02:10.063 --> 00:02:11.765 align:middle line:84%
how Rod made all
that magic happen.

00:02:11.765 --> 00:02:13.867 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: I will
always remember Serling coming

00:02:13.867 --> 00:02:15.602 align:middle line:90%
out talking about things right

00:02:15.602 --> 00:02:17.537 align:middle line:84%
after a little vignette
of the...

00:02:17.537 --> 00:02:18.939 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes.

00:02:18.939 --> 00:02:20.674 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: ...episode, and
then he'd go to a commercial.

00:02:20.674 --> 00:02:21.942 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yeah.

00:02:21.942 --> 00:02:23.210 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: And just
everything from the music,

00:02:23.210 --> 00:02:26.179 align:middle line:84%
to his style, to the
things that he did...

00:02:26.179 --> 00:02:27.514 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yeah.

00:02:27.514 --> 00:02:28.615 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: ...were just
unduplicatable [phonetic].

00:02:28.615 --> 00:02:30.016 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: No,
he was one of a kind.

00:02:30.016 --> 00:02:33.320 align:middle line:84%
And it's interesting because on
TV before Rod generally the --

00:02:33.320 --> 00:02:35.188 align:middle line:84%
generally the producers
ran the show,

00:02:35.188 --> 00:02:36.890 align:middle line:84%
and the writers were
subordinate to them.

00:02:36.890 --> 00:02:39.326 align:middle line:84%
But Rod really was the first
writer to say, "This is my show.

00:02:39.326 --> 00:02:40.694 align:middle line:90%
This is my stamp on it.

00:02:40.694 --> 00:02:43.463 align:middle line:84%
This is me presenting my
show to you, the audience."

00:02:43.463 --> 00:02:46.566 align:middle line:84%
And now writers run television;
writers run dramas and comedies.

00:02:46.566 --> 00:02:48.367 align:middle line:84%
And that led to J.J.
Abram, and Joss Whedon,

00:02:48.367 --> 00:02:50.470 align:middle line:84%
and all these amazing people
who are running shows now.

00:02:50.470 --> 00:02:52.038 align:middle line:84%
And Rod really set
the template for that.

00:02:52.038 --> 00:02:53.406 align:middle line:84%
He was -- he was
quite something.

00:02:53.406 --> 00:02:55.508 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: Did he
even think he would be

00:02:55.508 --> 00:02:58.111 align:middle line:84%
as successful as
he ended up being?

00:02:58.111 --> 00:03:01.748 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: Well, the funny
thing was the last interview he

00:03:01.748 --> 00:03:04.651 align:middle line:84%
gave before he died, sadly at
the age of 50, someone asked him

00:03:04.651 --> 00:03:05.885 align:middle line:90%
if he thought that his --

00:03:05.885 --> 00:03:07.587 align:middle line:84%
if he thought his work would
stand the test of time,

00:03:07.587 --> 00:03:09.756 align:middle line:84%
and he said, "Good
writing, like good wine,

00:03:09.756 --> 00:03:10.957 align:middle line:84%
has to age well with
time [laughter].

00:03:10.957 --> 00:03:13.260 align:middle line:84%
And my work has been
momentarily adequate."

00:03:13.260 --> 00:03:14.494 align:middle line:90%
And so he didn't know that --

00:03:14.494 --> 00:03:16.229 align:middle line:84%
that 50 years later his
work would be the classic it

00:03:16.229 --> 00:03:17.264 align:middle line:90%
has become.

00:03:17.264 --> 00:03:19.332 align:middle line:84%
So -- but he just
did an amazing job.

00:03:19.332 --> 00:03:20.867 align:middle line:84%
He was -- and he
dictated his scripts;

00:03:20.867 --> 00:03:21.968 align:middle line:90%
that was the amazing thing.

00:03:21.968 --> 00:03:23.069 align:middle line:84%
He would -- he would
wake in the morning...

00:03:23.069 --> 00:03:23.903 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: With
a little Dictaphone?

00:03:23.903 --> 00:03:24.604 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: That's right.

00:03:24.604 --> 00:03:25.739 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Yeah.

00:03:25.739 --> 00:03:26.973 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: He would
wake up in the morning,

00:03:26.973 --> 00:03:28.341 align:middle line:84%
go into his backyard,
lounge by his swimming pool,

00:03:28.341 --> 00:03:30.510 align:middle line:84%
and dictate  The Twilight Zone
scripts into a Dictaphone,

00:03:30.510 --> 00:03:32.278 align:middle line:84%
or later a cassette
recorder, and --

00:03:32.278 --> 00:03:34.180 align:middle line:84%
and then his secretary
would type them up,

00:03:34.180 --> 00:03:35.615 align:middle line:84%
and he'd make little
hand corrections.

00:03:35.615 --> 00:03:36.883 align:middle line:84%
So he used to joke that
he was the only writer

00:03:36.883 --> 00:03:38.785 align:middle line:84%
who could write a script
while getting a tan.

00:03:38.785 --> 00:03:39.753 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: That's amazing.

00:03:39.753 --> 00:03:40.620 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: So,
yeah [laughter].

00:03:40.620 --> 00:03:41.821 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
That is amazing.

00:03:41.821 --> 00:03:42.855 align:middle line:84%
And he would play the
characters and everything.

00:03:42.855 --> 00:03:43.790 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: He
would; he would.

00:03:43.790 --> 00:03:44.991 align:middle line:84%
He would basically
-- he would --

00:03:44.991 --> 00:03:46.793 align:middle line:84%
what Rod always said that
he was -- he was a ham.

00:03:46.793 --> 00:03:48.094 align:middle line:90%
You know a ham actor.

00:03:48.094 --> 00:03:50.597 align:middle line:84%
And so he really loved to
-- to go into the characters

00:03:50.597 --> 00:03:51.965 align:middle line:90%
and be the characters.

00:03:51.965 --> 00:03:53.867 align:middle line:84%
And -- and some of  The
Twilight Zone  episodes the --

00:03:53.867 --> 00:03:56.102 align:middle line:84%
it almost sounds like two Rod
Serlings talking to each other,

00:03:56.102 --> 00:03:58.138 align:middle line:84%
and that's because he
was very good with --

00:03:58.138 --> 00:03:59.072 align:middle line:90%
with dictating dialogue.

00:03:59.072 --> 00:04:00.507 align:middle line:84%
He was -- he was
quite phenomenal.

00:04:00.507 --> 00:04:03.777 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: He tried to
leak in his social commentary...

00:04:03.777 --> 00:04:05.011 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes.

00:04:05.011 --> 00:04:06.579 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: ...in a
very subtle way, didn't he?

00:04:06.579 --> 00:04:07.881 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yeah, he did.

00:04:07.881 --> 00:04:09.482 align:middle line:84%
And -- well, he was a -- he
was -- he was very much --

00:04:09.482 --> 00:04:10.817 align:middle line:84%
he was a liberal;
he was a humanist.

00:04:10.817 --> 00:04:12.485 align:middle line:84%
He really had -- was
rooting for the little guy,

00:04:12.485 --> 00:04:14.387 align:middle line:84%
and you can really
see that in his work,

00:04:14.387 --> 00:04:15.989 align:middle line:90%
that he has a great sympathy

00:04:15.989 --> 00:04:18.091 align:middle line:84%
for you know just --
just average folks.

00:04:18.091 --> 00:04:19.292 align:middle line:90%
You know most of the people

00:04:19.292 --> 00:04:21.093 align:middle line:84%
on  The Twilight Zone
aren't presidents, or --

00:04:21.093 --> 00:04:23.530 align:middle line:84%
or heads of state, or you
know -- or generals, or --

00:04:23.530 --> 00:04:25.465 align:middle line:90%
or anyone in -- in huge power.

00:04:25.465 --> 00:04:27.600 align:middle line:84%
They're usually the little guys,
bank tellers, salespersons...

00:04:27.600 --> 00:04:28.501 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
Right, troubled people.

00:04:28.501 --> 00:04:29.703 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Well, yes.

00:04:29.703 --> 00:04:31.104 align:middle line:84%
Women -- like "The
Hitchhiker" with Inger Stevens

00:04:31.104 --> 00:04:32.505 align:middle line:84%
where she's driving
cross country, and she...

00:04:32.505 --> 00:04:33.340 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Yeah.

00:04:33.340 --> 00:04:34.474 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: ...keeps seeing

00:04:34.474 --> 00:04:35.608 align:middle line:84%
that malevolent hitchhiker
wherever she goes.

00:04:35.608 --> 00:04:37.444 align:middle line:84%
He had the sympathy for
-- for the little guy.

00:04:37.444 --> 00:04:39.112 align:middle line:84%
And he -- and he
had a sense of that

00:04:39.112 --> 00:04:41.181 align:middle line:84%
if we all ban together we
can create a better life.

00:04:41.181 --> 00:04:43.583 align:middle line:84%
And  Twilight Zone  was very
much about moral choices

00:04:43.583 --> 00:04:46.286 align:middle line:84%
and people rising to
their best selves.

00:04:46.286 --> 00:04:48.455 align:middle line:84%
And -- and so there was
-- there's a great heart.

00:04:48.455 --> 00:04:50.857 align:middle line:84%
And I think that's why, even
when you've seen an episode,

00:04:50.857 --> 00:04:52.492 align:middle line:84%
and you know what
the twist ending is,

00:04:52.492 --> 00:04:54.494 align:middle line:84%
you can watch it again, and
again, and again because there's

00:04:54.494 --> 00:04:57.163 align:middle line:84%
such humanity in the
writing, whether it's Rod

00:04:57.163 --> 00:04:58.431 align:middle line:84%
or the other writers
who worked on the show.

00:04:58.431 --> 00:05:00.900 align:middle line:84%
Rod wrote -- there
were 156 episodes;

00:05:00.900 --> 00:05:02.268 align:middle line:90%
he wrote 92 of them himself.

00:05:02.268 --> 00:05:03.670 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: That's
-- that's extensive.

00:05:03.670 --> 00:05:05.004 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: It's amazing.

00:05:05.004 --> 00:05:06.573 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: Now where
did he find the other writers?

00:05:06.573 --> 00:05:08.608 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: Well, this is
a story -- you know it's funny.

00:05:08.608 --> 00:05:10.677 align:middle line:84%
When I wrote  The Twilight Zone
Companion  there was someone I

00:05:10.677 --> 00:05:13.446 align:middle line:84%
wanted to interview, and he
declined to be interviewed.

00:05:13.446 --> 00:05:15.781 align:middle line:84%
He -- he was very gracious about
it, but was Ray Bradbury, our --

00:05:15.781 --> 00:05:16.783 align:middle line:90%
our dear friend Ray Bradbury.

00:05:16.783 --> 00:05:17.817 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
God rest his soul.

00:05:17.817 --> 00:05:19.185 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Sadly missed.

00:05:19.185 --> 00:05:21.788 align:middle line:84%
And -- but in -- in the last
15 years Ray became a very good

00:05:21.788 --> 00:05:23.256 align:middle line:90%
friend of mine.

00:05:23.256 --> 00:05:24.557 align:middle line:84%
And so I said, "Okay, talk to
me about  Twilight Zone , Ray,"

00:05:24.557 --> 00:05:25.692 align:middle line:84%
because he and --
he and Rod had --

00:05:25.692 --> 00:05:27.093 align:middle line:84%
had had a little bit
of a falling out.

00:05:27.093 --> 00:05:30.263 align:middle line:84%
But he told me that when
Twilight Zone  was green lit,

00:05:30.263 --> 00:05:32.565 align:middle line:84%
when Rod sold the show,
he called Ray Bradbury,

00:05:32.565 --> 00:05:35.001 align:middle line:84%
and he said, "I don't know
anything about science fiction.

00:05:35.001 --> 00:05:36.970 align:middle line:84%
Help me." And so
Ray said, "Well,

00:05:36.970 --> 00:05:38.071 align:middle line:90%
come on over to the house."

00:05:38.071 --> 00:05:39.539 align:middle line:84%
And -- and he took --
he took Rod Serling

00:05:39.539 --> 00:05:40.840 align:middle line:90%
down into his basement --

00:05:40.840 --> 00:05:42.308 align:middle line:84%
Ray Bradbury at that point
was already the top science

00:05:42.308 --> 00:05:43.009 align:middle line:90%
fiction writer.

00:05:43.009 --> 00:05:43.977 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Sure.

00:05:43.977 --> 00:05:45.044 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: And
he said, "Okay."

00:05:45.044 --> 00:05:46.413 align:middle line:84%
And he pulled some
books from his shelf.

00:05:46.413 --> 00:05:47.647 align:middle line:84%
One was by John Collier, who
was a very famous short story

00:05:47.647 --> 00:05:48.781 align:middle line:90%
writer, British.

00:05:48.781 --> 00:05:51.151 align:middle line:84%
One was by George -- one
was by Charles Beaumont;

00:05:51.151 --> 00:05:52.719 align:middle line:90%
one was by Richard Matheson.

00:05:52.719 --> 00:05:53.753 align:middle line:90%
They were two of his proteges.

00:05:53.753 --> 00:05:55.588 align:middle line:84%
And one was a book
by Ray himself.

00:05:55.588 --> 00:05:57.791 align:middle line:84%
And he said, "Read these,
and then let's talk."

00:05:57.791 --> 00:06:00.593 align:middle line:84%
And so Serling ended up adapting
one of John Collier's stories --

00:06:00.593 --> 00:06:02.262 align:middle line:84%
stories for  Twilight
Zone  , but he brought --

00:06:02.262 --> 00:06:03.997 align:middle line:84%
he brought Beaumont
and Matheson aboard

00:06:03.997 --> 00:06:05.932 align:middle line:84%
as his main writers
beyond himself,

00:06:05.932 --> 00:06:08.468 align:middle line:84%
and they wrote amazing episodes
like "Nightmare at 20,000 Feet"

00:06:08.468 --> 00:06:09.335 align:middle line:90%
with the gremlin on the wing.

00:06:09.335 --> 00:06:10.170 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
I love that one.

00:06:10.170 --> 00:06:11.004 align:middle line:90%
That was with Shatner, right?

00:06:11.004 --> 00:06:11.571 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes, Shatner.

00:06:11.571 --> 00:06:12.505 align:middle line:90%
Great episode.

00:06:12.505 --> 00:06:13.907 align:middle line:84%
And -- and so that
became his core.

00:06:13.907 --> 00:06:15.809 align:middle line:84%
So -- so Ray Bradbury
was very instrumental

00:06:15.809 --> 00:06:17.510 align:middle line:84%
in shaping what  Twilight
Zone  became.

00:06:17.510 --> 00:06:18.578 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Super.

00:06:18.578 --> 00:06:20.046 align:middle line:84%
We've got some vignettes
that I want to --

00:06:20.046 --> 00:06:21.848 align:middle line:84%
to show to our  Beyond
Belief  audience.

00:06:21.848 --> 00:06:23.183 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Great.

00:06:23.183 --> 00:06:23.783 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: Now the first
is "Nothing in the Dark."

00:06:23.783 --> 00:06:24.451 align:middle line:90%
Tell us a...

00:06:24.451 --> 00:06:25.518 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes.

00:06:25.518 --> 00:06:26.219 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
...little bit about that.

00:06:26.219 --> 00:06:27.420 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Well,

00:06:27.420 --> 00:06:28.455 align:middle line:84%
George Clayton Johnson
was the other great writer

00:06:28.455 --> 00:06:29.656 align:middle line:84%
of  The Twilight
Zone , and "Nothing

00:06:29.656 --> 00:06:31.057 align:middle line:84%
in the Dark" stars Gladys
Cooper as an old woman

00:06:31.057 --> 00:06:33.326 align:middle line:84%
who has barricaded herself in
her apartment because she's sure

00:06:33.326 --> 00:06:35.228 align:middle line:84%
that death will come
in some disguise...

00:06:35.228 --> 00:06:36.229 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Ah.

00:06:36.229 --> 00:06:37.197 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: ...and
take her away.

00:06:37.197 --> 00:06:38.598 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
And -- and get her.

00:06:38.598 --> 00:06:39.632 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: And then one day
she hears gunfire outside her

00:06:39.632 --> 00:06:41.801 align:middle line:84%
apartment, and a
policeman has been shot,

00:06:41.801 --> 00:06:43.970 align:middle line:84%
and he's begging
her to help him.

00:06:43.970 --> 00:06:45.872 align:middle line:84%
And -- and her compassion
overcomes her fear,

00:06:45.872 --> 00:06:47.740 align:middle line:84%
and she brings him
into her apartment.

00:06:47.740 --> 00:06:50.543 align:middle line:84%
And it's this amazing piece --
George Clayton Johnson was --

00:06:50.543 --> 00:06:52.445 align:middle line:84%
was barely 30 when
he wrote that script,

00:06:52.445 --> 00:06:54.781 align:middle line:84%
but it's this real rumination
on old age, and death,

00:06:54.781 --> 00:06:57.217 align:middle line:84%
and fear of death, and
moving on, and being part

00:06:57.217 --> 00:06:58.551 align:middle line:90%
of the larger universe.

00:06:58.551 --> 00:07:01.955 align:middle line:84%
It's an amazing piece of
writing, and to play the --

00:07:01.955 --> 00:07:03.656 align:middle line:84%
the cop they -- they
got a young actor

00:07:03.656 --> 00:07:05.725 align:middle line:84%
who hadn't done very much
-- at that point he hadn't.

00:07:05.725 --> 00:07:08.194 align:middle line:84%
He was -- he wasn't really well
known, but it's Robert Redford.

00:07:08.194 --> 00:07:09.329 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Ah!

00:07:09.329 --> 00:07:10.697 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: And it's
just an amazing cast.

00:07:10.697 --> 00:07:11.531 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: He jump-started
so many careers, didn't he?

00:07:11.531 --> 00:07:12.365 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Indeed, indeed.

00:07:12.365 --> 00:07:13.333 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: That's cool.

00:07:13.333 --> 00:07:14.634 align:middle line:84%
Let's take a little
look at this.

00:07:14.634 --> 00:07:21.406 align:middle line:84%
>> [Background Music]
It's time to rest.

00:07:21.406 --> 00:07:25.011 align:middle line:90%
Give me your hand.

00:07:25.011 --> 00:07:27.447 align:middle line:90%
>> I don't want to die.

00:07:28.715 --> 00:07:35.522 align:middle line:90%
>> Trust me.

00:07:35.522 --> 00:07:35.922 align:middle line:90%
>> No [crying].

00:07:35.922 --> 00:07:36.856 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:07:37.891 --> 00:07:42.161 align:middle line:90%
>> Mother, give me your hand.

00:07:42.161 --> 00:07:47.200 align:middle line:90%
[ Music ]

00:07:47.200 --> 00:07:48.401 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
He was a genius.

00:07:48.401 --> 00:07:49.269 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: That's
such a great, good scene.

00:07:49.269 --> 00:07:50.537 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
He took death...

00:07:50.537 --> 00:07:51.905 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yeah.

00:07:51.905 --> 00:07:53.473 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: ...and made
it to this little, old lady...

00:07:53.473 --> 00:07:54.340 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Right.

00:07:54.340 --> 00:07:55.575 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
...sound, "Well,

00:07:55.575 --> 00:07:57.076 align:middle line:90%
maybe it's not all that bad."

00:07:57.076 --> 00:07:58.311 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes.

00:07:58.311 --> 00:07:59.812 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: And he took
a -- a good-looking guy,

00:07:59.812 --> 00:08:03.483 align:middle line:84%
Robert Redford, and just made
it very comfortable for her.

00:08:03.483 --> 00:08:05.118 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes, well I
mean, it's -- it's interesting.

00:08:05.118 --> 00:08:08.187 align:middle line:84%
It's rare that you have
work that is profound.

00:08:08.187 --> 00:08:10.390 align:middle line:84%
And  Twilight Zone  again,
and again, and again comes

00:08:10.390 --> 00:08:12.091 align:middle line:84%
to a profound truth
about all our lives.

00:08:12.091 --> 00:08:13.893 align:middle line:84%
And it's amazing even
in that scene where --

00:08:13.893 --> 00:08:16.362 align:middle line:84%
first of all, it's gorgeously
lit, gorgeously performed.

00:08:16.362 --> 00:08:17.697 align:middle line:90%
The -- the directing is great;

00:08:17.697 --> 00:08:19.465 align:middle line:84%
the writing is great;
the acting is superb.

00:08:19.465 --> 00:08:20.600 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: Something
about black-and-white...

00:08:20.600 --> 00:08:21.434 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yeah.

00:08:21.434 --> 00:08:22.769 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: ...film, truly.

00:08:22.769 --> 00:08:24.037 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: And -- and I
asked George Clayton Johnson

00:08:24.037 --> 00:08:25.104 align:middle line:84%
when -- when I was talking
to him about this episode,

00:08:25.104 --> 00:08:25.939 align:middle line:84%
you know Robert Redford
calls her mother,

00:08:25.939 --> 00:08:27.073 align:middle line:90%
and he's -- he's not her son.

00:08:27.073 --> 00:08:29.642 align:middle line:90%
He's death personified, but --

00:08:29.642 --> 00:08:33.146 align:middle line:84%
but George's idea was he's
speaking to her as a mother...

00:08:33.146 --> 00:08:34.280 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Right.

00:08:34.280 --> 00:08:35.647 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: ...as --
you know so there's --

00:08:35.647 --> 00:08:37.450 align:middle line:84%
he's speaking to her as her
role in life, as her humanity.

00:08:37.450 --> 00:08:40.520 align:middle line:84%
And there's just this great
wisdom in the writing, and --

00:08:40.520 --> 00:08:42.421 align:middle line:84%
and that's why it's
stood the test of time.

00:08:42.421 --> 00:08:44.457 align:middle line:84%
You know, great work
stands the test of time.

00:08:44.457 --> 00:08:45.658 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: Unlike
A Christmas Carol

00:08:45.658 --> 00:08:47.860 align:middle line:84%
where death shows up with
that black hood and...

00:08:47.860 --> 00:08:49.162 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes.

00:08:49.162 --> 00:08:49.829 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: ...you know
you don't see his face...

00:08:49.829 --> 00:08:51.197 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes.

00:08:51.197 --> 00:08:51.965 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: ...and this
bony little hand, and stuff...

00:08:51.965 --> 00:08:52.799 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yeah.

00:08:52.799 --> 00:08:53.766 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: ...like that.

00:08:53.766 --> 00:08:55.168 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: And
-- and George --

00:08:55.168 --> 00:08:56.569 align:middle line:84%
George told me that the whole
point was that death is not a --

00:08:56.569 --> 00:08:59.439 align:middle line:84%
isn't something to be feared;
it's something to be embraced.

00:08:59.439 --> 00:09:02.308 align:middle line:84%
And -- and George
now is in his 80s,

00:09:02.308 --> 00:09:03.676 align:middle line:84%
and so it's very
interesting to see --

00:09:03.676 --> 00:09:04.811 align:middle line:84%
to talk to him about
these episodes.

00:09:04.811 --> 00:09:06.179 align:middle line:84%
When we did the audio
commentaries

00:09:06.179 --> 00:09:09.282 align:middle line:84%
for the Blu-Ray I got to talk
to George Clayton Johnson

00:09:09.282 --> 00:09:11.284 align:middle line:84%
about all the episodes
he wrote, and it's funny.

00:09:11.284 --> 00:09:13.486 align:middle line:84%
Now what he says is when -- when
he himself sees death coming

00:09:13.486 --> 00:09:14.721 align:middle line:84%
for him he's going to
side step him [laughter],

00:09:14.721 --> 00:09:16.222 align:middle line:90%
so that's his plan.

00:09:16.222 --> 00:09:17.657 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
Was there a message

00:09:17.657 --> 00:09:20.560 align:middle line:84%
in every  Twilight
Zone  episode?

00:09:20.560 --> 00:09:22.061 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes, in
most of them I think,

00:09:22.061 --> 00:09:23.263 align:middle line:90%
or perhaps in all of them.

00:09:23.263 --> 00:09:25.264 align:middle line:84%
I mean, basically --
and as a writer...

00:09:25.264 --> 00:09:25.965 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: I
mean, he know it was...

00:09:25.965 --> 00:09:26.899 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yeah.

00:09:26.899 --> 00:09:27.567 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
...entertainment.

00:09:27.567 --> 00:09:28.268 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes.

00:09:28.268 --> 00:09:29.636 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Right?

00:09:29.636 --> 00:09:30.336 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: He did, and
that's the first obligation...

00:09:30.336 --> 00:09:31.304 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Yeah.

00:09:31.304 --> 00:09:32.138 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: ...of
any writer.

00:09:32.138 --> 00:09:33.273 align:middle line:90%
You have to entertain someone.

00:09:33.273 --> 00:09:34.374 align:middle line:84%
If you're -- if you're
lecturing them and --

00:09:34.374 --> 00:09:35.008 align:middle line:84%
and being tedious you're
-- what's the point?

00:09:35.008 --> 00:09:36.175 align:middle line:90%
You're going to...

00:09:36.175 --> 00:09:36.943 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: You
lose your audience, yeah.

00:09:36.943 --> 00:09:38.344 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Of course.

00:09:38.344 --> 00:09:39.345 align:middle line:84%
But -- but what Rod taught me
as a writer is you have to look

00:09:39.345 --> 00:09:40.046 align:middle line:84%
in -- well, Ray Bradbury
said this, too;

00:09:40.046 --> 00:09:41.147 align:middle line:90%
he said, "Look inside.

00:09:41.147 --> 00:09:42.282 align:middle line:84%
Rather than looking
outside, look inside.

00:09:42.282 --> 00:09:43.816 align:middle line:84%
Find your heart; find
what you truly believe;

00:09:43.816 --> 00:09:45.385 align:middle line:90%
find what you truly care about.

00:09:45.385 --> 00:09:46.519 align:middle line:90%
Write from that."

00:09:46.519 --> 00:09:48.154 align:middle line:84%
And Rod -- Rod actually
used to talk about this.

00:09:48.154 --> 00:09:50.823 align:middle line:84%
Rod Serling was talking to a --
to a class, and he was saying,

00:09:50.823 --> 00:09:53.459 align:middle line:84%
"Whenever I write I --
I ask myself, is this --

00:09:53.459 --> 00:09:55.528 align:middle line:90%
is this the truth as I know it?

00:09:55.528 --> 00:09:57.363 align:middle line:90%
Or better yet, as I feel it?"

00:09:57.363 --> 00:09:58.698 align:middle line:90%
And that was what guided him.

00:09:58.698 --> 00:10:00.667 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: The next
clip is also a great message,

00:10:00.667 --> 00:10:04.470 align:middle line:84%
one of my favorites, which
has helped steer me in  Coast

00:10:04.470 --> 00:10:06.739 align:middle line:90%
to Coast , is "To Serve Man."

00:10:06.739 --> 00:10:07.940 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes.

00:10:07.940 --> 00:10:09.075 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: Tell me
the theme behind this one.

00:10:09.075 --> 00:10:10.309 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: Well,
"To Serve Man" is based

00:10:10.309 --> 00:10:11.844 align:middle line:84%
on a very famous science
fiction short story written

00:10:11.844 --> 00:10:13.012 align:middle line:90%
by Damon Knight who was one

00:10:13.012 --> 00:10:14.847 align:middle line:84%
of my writing teachers,
interestingly enough.

00:10:14.847 --> 00:10:17.517 align:middle line:84%
And Damon told me that he
wrote that story one night

00:10:17.517 --> 00:10:19.819 align:middle line:84%
when his wife was out with
another man, and so he was

00:10:19.819 --> 00:10:21.454 align:middle line:84%
in a very [laughter]
dark -- very dark...

00:10:21.454 --> 00:10:22.155 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Yeah.

00:10:22.155 --> 00:10:23.089 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: ...mood.

00:10:23.089 --> 00:10:23.923 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
I would think so.

00:10:23.923 --> 00:10:25.124 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Very dark mood,

00:10:25.124 --> 00:10:26.025 align:middle line:84%
and so Rod of course read
the story and adapted it

00:10:26.025 --> 00:10:27.460 align:middle line:90%
to a  Twilight Zone  episode,

00:10:27.460 --> 00:10:28.895 align:middle line:84%
and it's a great  Twilight Zone
episode about aliens coming

00:10:28.895 --> 00:10:31.864 align:middle line:84%
to Earth who supposedly are very
benevolent, and they just want

00:10:31.864 --> 00:10:34.300 align:middle line:90%
to supposedly to serve man.

00:10:34.300 --> 00:10:36.969 align:middle line:84%
And -- and it's fascinating
because in that episode --

00:10:36.969 --> 00:10:39.205 align:middle line:84%
I recently was talking with
Richard Bare who directed it;

00:10:39.205 --> 00:10:41.174 align:middle line:84%
he's going to be 100 in
August, this -- this director.

00:10:41.174 --> 00:10:41.841 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Wow!

00:10:41.841 --> 00:10:43.042 align:middle line:90%
Still going strong?

00:10:43.042 --> 00:10:43.743 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: Still
going strong, amazing man.

00:10:43.743 --> 00:10:44.711 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Yeah.

00:10:44.711 --> 00:10:46.045 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: And
it's fascinating

00:10:46.045 --> 00:10:47.146 align:middle line:84%
because this episode is unlike
Twilight Zone  episodes

00:10:47.146 --> 00:10:48.481 align:middle line:84%
in general because
it has a character

00:10:48.481 --> 00:10:50.817 align:middle line:84%
who actually talks directly
to the camera, not just Rod.

00:10:50.817 --> 00:10:53.386 align:middle line:84%
And -- and the aliens were
all played by one actor,

00:10:53.386 --> 00:10:54.654 align:middle line:90%
Richard Kiel, who was

00:10:54.654 --> 00:10:56.589 align:middle line:84%
around seven feet
tall, seven foot, two.

00:10:56.589 --> 00:10:59.192 align:middle line:84%
He later played the character
Jaws in the James Bond movies.

00:10:59.192 --> 00:11:01.761 align:middle line:84%
But -- but it was a fascinating
thing because he looks --

00:11:01.761 --> 00:11:04.964 align:middle line:84%
he looks a little bit angelic,
and a little bit devilish.

00:11:04.964 --> 00:11:05.998 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Yes.

00:11:05.998 --> 00:11:07.400 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: A
little bit corrupt,

00:11:07.400 --> 00:11:09.302 align:middle line:84%
and it's a great make-up, and
-- and just a terrific episode.

00:11:09.302 --> 00:11:10.570 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: Let's
take a look at this one.

00:11:10.570 --> 00:11:19.645 align:middle line:84%
>> [Radio static] This
is flight number 914

00:11:20.513 --> 00:11:25.051 align:middle line:90%
from earth to our planet.

00:11:25.051 --> 00:11:28.020 align:middle line:84%
We will be taking
off in three minutes.

00:11:28.020 --> 00:11:28.721 align:middle line:90%
>> Mr. Chambers!

00:11:28.721 --> 00:11:30.923 align:middle line:90%
Mr. Chambers!

00:11:30.923 --> 00:11:34.227 align:middle line:90%
Don't get on that ship!

00:11:34.227 --> 00:11:40.266 align:middle line:84%
The rest of the book,
To Serve Men , it's --

00:11:40.266 --> 00:11:41.868 align:middle line:84%
it's a cookbook [Background
Music]!

00:11:41.868 --> 00:11:43.736 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: Oh [laughter],
dinner is served, Marc.

00:11:43.736 --> 00:11:44.937 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes,
that's so great [laughter].

00:11:44.937 --> 00:11:46.339 align:middle line:90%
That's so great.

00:11:46.339 --> 00:11:47.507 align:middle line:84%
And of course that -- that's one
of the great snappers at the end

00:11:47.507 --> 00:11:48.775 align:middle line:84%
of these  Twilight
Zone  episodes.

00:11:48.775 --> 00:11:49.742 align:middle line:90%
But you know one thing was --

00:11:49.742 --> 00:11:51.077 align:middle line:84%
that's really great
when you watch

00:11:51.077 --> 00:11:53.045 align:middle line:84%
that little clip is  Twilight
Zone  was shot at MGM,

00:11:53.045 --> 00:11:56.249 align:middle line:84%
and that was the greatest
studio ever, and they --

00:11:56.249 --> 00:11:58.918 align:middle line:84%
and Rod had access to all
the props, all the costumes,

00:11:58.918 --> 00:12:01.387 align:middle line:84%
all the sets ever
built for any MGM...

00:12:01.387 --> 00:12:02.255 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Any episode?

00:12:02.255 --> 00:12:03.656 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: ...movie
-- yeah.

00:12:03.656 --> 00:12:05.057 align:middle line:84%
And so -- so that little landing
thing, the bottom of the saucer,

00:12:05.057 --> 00:12:06.225 align:middle line:84%
is right out of  Forbidden
Planet .

00:12:06.225 --> 00:12:08.361 align:middle line:84%
It was built for
Forbidden Planet , and so --

00:12:08.361 --> 00:12:11.731 align:middle line:84%
so  Twilight Zone  benefitted
from that enormous wealth of --

00:12:11.731 --> 00:12:13.733 align:middle line:84%
of props and costumes and
sets that they could access.

00:12:13.733 --> 00:12:15.601 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
Who's the guy's voice?

00:12:15.601 --> 00:12:18.671 align:middle line:84%
The announcer's voice when you
heard that at the beginning?

00:12:18.671 --> 00:12:19.739 align:middle line:90%
Because I've heard him...

00:12:19.739 --> 00:12:20.706 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yeah.

00:12:20.706 --> 00:12:22.041 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
...on other things.

00:12:22.041 --> 00:12:23.042 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: Yeah, well
Marvin Miller was a terrific --

00:12:23.042 --> 00:12:25.344 align:middle line:84%
terrific old voiceover
guy, so yeah.

00:12:25.344 --> 00:12:26.145 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Okay.

00:12:26.145 --> 00:12:26.946 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yeah, yeah.

00:12:26.946 --> 00:12:28.080 align:middle line:90%
That's -- that's great, so.

00:12:28.080 --> 00:12:29.282 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: Well,
you know what's so great

00:12:29.282 --> 00:12:32.251 align:middle line:84%
about what Serling did,
too, is he created jobs...

00:12:32.251 --> 00:12:33.252 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes.

00:12:33.252 --> 00:12:33.920 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
...for emerging people.

00:12:33.920 --> 00:12:34.787 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes.

00:12:34.787 --> 00:12:36.322 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
Writers, talent,

00:12:36.322 --> 00:12:38.457 align:middle line:84%
people who really
never would have had

00:12:38.457 --> 00:12:40.059 align:middle line:90%
that opportunity in Hollywood.

00:12:40.059 --> 00:12:40.893 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: That's right.

00:12:40.893 --> 00:12:42.228 align:middle line:90%
Well, you know it's very funny

00:12:42.228 --> 00:12:43.496 align:middle line:84%
because Charles Beaumont had
already been writing for TV,

00:12:43.496 --> 00:12:46.364 align:middle line:84%
but westerns, things like
Wanted Dead or Alive ,

00:12:46.364 --> 00:12:47.867 align:middle line:84%
and he was used to
writing stuff,

00:12:47.867 --> 00:12:49.702 align:middle line:84%
and they would just take it,
and chew it up, and spit it out,

00:12:49.702 --> 00:12:51.003 align:middle line:90%
and it wouldn't bear anything --

00:12:51.003 --> 00:12:53.005 align:middle line:84%
it wouldn't look anything
like what he'd written.

00:12:53.005 --> 00:12:55.141 align:middle line:84%
And Rod said to him,
"You write it,

00:12:55.141 --> 00:12:56.309 align:middle line:90%
and we'll shoot what you write.

00:12:56.309 --> 00:12:57.810 align:middle line:90%
We will honor you as a writer."

00:12:57.810 --> 00:12:59.745 align:middle line:84%
And Beaumont thought,
"Well, good luck with that."

00:12:59.745 --> 00:13:01.214 align:middle line:84%
But he said, "Well, I'll --
I'll just take a run at it,"

00:13:01.214 --> 00:13:03.649 align:middle line:84%
and he wrote the script,
and he was astonished

00:13:03.649 --> 00:13:05.084 align:middle line:90%
that Rod shot what he wrote.

00:13:05.084 --> 00:13:06.819 align:middle line:84%
And I -- I've seen the first
drafts of these scripts

00:13:06.819 --> 00:13:08.120 align:middle line:84%
by Richard Matheson,
and Beaumont,

00:13:08.120 --> 00:13:10.189 align:middle line:84%
and George Clayton Johnson,
and that's what they shot.

00:13:10.189 --> 00:13:13.426 align:middle line:84%
And in fact when Rod
won his second Emmy

00:13:13.426 --> 00:13:15.528 align:middle line:84%
for  Twilight Zone  he
held it up on camera,

00:13:15.528 --> 00:13:17.096 align:middle line:84%
and he named [laughter] -- he
named George Clayton Johnson,

00:13:17.096 --> 00:13:18.397 align:middle line:84%
and Charles Beaumont,
and Richard Matheson.

00:13:18.397 --> 00:13:19.665 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Class.

00:13:19.665 --> 00:13:20.700 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: He said,
"Come over to my house, guys,

00:13:20.700 --> 00:13:21.400 align:middle line:84%
and we'll carve this
up like a turkey."

00:13:21.400 --> 00:13:22.768 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Yeah.

00:13:22.768 --> 00:13:23.703 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: So that was --
yeah, exactly, a classy guy.

00:13:23.703 --> 00:13:24.670 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
Class all the way.

00:13:24.670 --> 00:13:26.038 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: Yeah,
you got it.

00:13:26.038 --> 00:13:26.873 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: Let's take
some questions for Marc Zicree

00:13:26.873 --> 00:13:27.640 align:middle line:90%
about  The Twilight Zone .

00:13:27.640 --> 00:13:28.407 align:middle line:90%
Who's got one?

00:13:28.407 --> 00:13:31.143 align:middle line:90%
It's one of our favorites.

00:13:32.712 --> 00:13:34.313 align:middle line:90%
Don't be shy.

00:13:35.882 --> 00:13:37.884 align:middle line:84%
I'm doing such a thorough job
[laughter] you don't have any

00:13:37.884 --> 00:13:40.453 align:middle line:90%
questions, right?

00:13:40.453 --> 00:13:41.153 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:13:41.153 --> 00:13:42.555 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yeah?

00:13:42.555 --> 00:13:44.290 align:middle line:84%
>> Do you think the -- the show
would have been as good in color

00:13:44.290 --> 00:13:45.958 align:middle line:90%
as it was in black-and-white?

00:13:45.958 --> 00:13:47.493 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: You know I --
I love the black-and-white.

00:13:47.493 --> 00:13:51.497 align:middle line:84%
I think that it's the greatest
black-and-white television show

00:13:51.497 --> 00:13:52.098 align:middle line:90%
ever made.

00:13:52.098 --> 00:13:53.232 align:middle line:90%
It's gorgeous.

00:13:53.232 --> 00:13:54.634 align:middle line:84%
George Clemens was the
Director of Photography,

00:13:54.634 --> 00:13:56.769 align:middle line:84%
and he had been a cameraman
on you know Valentino's  Blood

00:13:56.769 --> 00:13:58.771 align:middle line:84%
and Sand  and Fredric
March  Jekyll and Hyde .

00:13:58.771 --> 00:14:01.774 align:middle line:84%
He'd really learned his craft,
and so it's -- it's gorgeous.

00:14:01.774 --> 00:14:03.242 align:middle line:84%
I think -- I think if
it had been in color --

00:14:03.242 --> 00:14:04.243 align:middle line:84%
in color it wouldn't
have been as good.

00:14:04.243 --> 00:14:05.845 align:middle line:84%
I think it would
have lost something.

00:14:05.845 --> 00:14:07.613 align:middle line:84%
And you know when they
brought  Twilight Zone  back

00:14:07.613 --> 00:14:10.283 align:middle line:84%
as a series a couple times in
more recent years they shot it

00:14:10.283 --> 00:14:12.184 align:middle line:84%
in color, and so it was
missing Rod Serling,

00:14:12.184 --> 00:14:13.619 align:middle line:84%
and it was missing
black-and-white, and it --

00:14:13.619 --> 00:14:15.988 align:middle line:84%
and both times it just
wasn't what the original show

00:14:15.988 --> 00:14:17.089 align:middle line:90%
had been.

00:14:17.089 --> 00:14:17.790 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: I think
you're right, Marc.

00:14:17.790 --> 00:14:18.958 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yeah.

00:14:18.958 --> 00:14:20.259 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: And
when the subsequent show,

00:14:20.259 --> 00:14:21.694 align:middle line:90%
Night Gallery , came out...

00:14:21.694 --> 00:14:22.662 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes.

00:14:22.662 --> 00:14:23.663 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
...it was in color,

00:14:23.663 --> 00:14:26.132 align:middle line:84%
and I remember feeling
disappointed.

00:14:26.132 --> 00:14:26.966 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes.

00:14:26.966 --> 00:14:28.000 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: You know I --

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:30.603 align:middle line:84%
I wanted that Rod
Serling-esque feel,

00:14:30.603 --> 00:14:33.072 align:middle line:84%
and he didn't have total
control on  Night Gallery .

00:14:33.072 --> 00:14:33.572 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: No, he didn't.

00:14:33.572 --> 00:14:34.640 align:middle line:90%
He didn't.

00:14:34.640 --> 00:14:35.474 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: But
I think when we went

00:14:35.474 --> 00:14:36.943 align:middle line:90%
from black-and-white to color...

00:14:36.943 --> 00:14:37.743 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yeah.

00:14:37.743 --> 00:14:38.711 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: ...it kind

00:14:38.711 --> 00:14:39.812 align:middle line:84%
of changed the mood
and the feeling.

00:14:39.812 --> 00:14:41.213 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: Yeah,
and you know it's --

00:14:41.213 --> 00:14:45.484 align:middle line:84%
there's just something so classy
about black-and-white, and so --

00:14:45.484 --> 00:14:47.520 align:middle line:84%
I mean, when you look at the
lighting on the actor's faces,

00:14:47.520 --> 00:14:48.788 align:middle line:84%
or they'd -- they'd
wet down the streets,

00:14:48.788 --> 00:14:51.223 align:middle line:84%
and you'd see those reflections,
and it just takes you

00:14:51.223 --> 00:14:52.358 align:middle line:90%
into that world you know.

00:14:52.358 --> 00:14:53.726 align:middle line:84%
And it's funny because
the current wisdom --

00:14:53.726 --> 00:14:55.328 align:middle line:84%
wisdom now is that people don't
want to see black-and-white,

00:14:55.328 --> 00:14:58.864 align:middle line:84%
but I think that wisdom is wrong
[laughter], because I think

00:14:58.864 --> 00:15:01.634 align:middle line:84%
when something is done
brilliantly people will --

00:15:01.634 --> 00:15:02.969 align:middle line:90%
will go where it takes you.

00:15:02.969 --> 00:15:04.770 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: Talking about
technology, we've got a...

00:15:04.770 --> 00:15:05.771 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes.

00:15:05.771 --> 00:15:06.572 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
...question from you --

00:15:06.572 --> 00:15:07.673 align:middle line:90%
for you, Marc, way out here.

00:15:07.673 --> 00:15:08.808 align:middle line:90%
Let's listen in.

00:15:08.808 --> 00:15:09.942 align:middle line:90%
>> Hey, Marc.

00:15:09.942 --> 00:15:11.544 align:middle line:90%
This is Leah from Philly,

00:15:11.544 --> 00:15:13.980 align:middle line:84%
and I want to know why
you think Rod Serling was

00:15:13.980 --> 00:15:16.515 align:middle line:90%
so far ahead of his time.

00:15:16.515 --> 00:15:18.951 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: And he was,
yes, so far ahead of his time.

00:15:18.951 --> 00:15:21.187 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: You know, it's
fascinating because Rod was a --

00:15:21.187 --> 00:15:24.256 align:middle line:84%
during the 50s he was writing
realistic, hard-hitting dramas

00:15:24.256 --> 00:15:26.592 align:middle line:84%
for -- for live television,
like  Requiem for a Heavyweight

00:15:26.592 --> 00:15:28.627 align:middle line:84%
and  Patterns , and he was
winning all these Emmys.

00:15:28.627 --> 00:15:29.895 align:middle line:84%
But whenever he tried
to write something

00:15:29.895 --> 00:15:32.864 align:middle line:84%
that was controversial
dealing with politics, or race,

00:15:32.864 --> 00:15:34.700 align:middle line:84%
or social issues,
they would censor him,

00:15:34.700 --> 00:15:36.836 align:middle line:84%
and so his message
would be totally lost.

00:15:36.836 --> 00:15:39.705 align:middle line:84%
And so he wrote  Twilight Zone
not because he wanted to escape

00:15:39.705 --> 00:15:43.075 align:middle line:84%
from reality, but his idea
was to hide his message

00:15:43.075 --> 00:15:45.845 align:middle line:84%
so the censors wouldn't get
it, but the audience would.

00:15:45.845 --> 00:15:48.748 align:middle line:84%
And in doing that
he made it timeless,

00:15:48.748 --> 00:15:50.316 align:middle line:84%
because if you see something
like "Eye of the Beholder"

00:15:50.316 --> 00:15:51.917 align:middle line:84%
where the woman's head
is wrapped in bandages,

00:15:51.917 --> 00:15:53.319 align:middle line:84%
and she just wants
to look normal,

00:15:53.319 --> 00:15:54.687 align:middle line:84%
or at least [laughter]
accepted as normal.

00:15:54.687 --> 00:15:55.921 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
I know that one.

00:15:55.921 --> 00:15:57.056 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: It's great,
and he's dealing with --

00:15:57.056 --> 00:15:58.791 align:middle line:84%
you know when you think
about issues of dealing

00:15:58.791 --> 00:16:01.494 align:middle line:84%
with the handicapped and the
disabled, and here's Rod have --

00:16:01.494 --> 00:16:04.530 align:middle line:84%
writing this role for this woman
who's supposedly disfigured,

00:16:04.530 --> 00:16:06.232 align:middle line:84%
but she just wants
to be accepted.

00:16:06.232 --> 00:16:09.168 align:middle line:84%
And -- and so he was ahead of
his time because he was coming

00:16:09.168 --> 00:16:12.371 align:middle line:84%
from a deep, deep
understanding of humanity

00:16:12.371 --> 00:16:13.973 align:middle line:90%
and a deep compassion.

00:16:13.973 --> 00:16:15.107 align:middle line:90%
And I think when you come

00:16:15.107 --> 00:16:17.076 align:middle line:84%
from those places
your work will speak

00:16:17.076 --> 00:16:18.277 align:middle line:90%
to generation after generation.

00:16:18.277 --> 00:16:20.246 align:middle line:90%
It won't -- it won't be dated.

00:16:20.246 --> 00:16:22.048 align:middle line:84%
And it's fascinating because
Twilight Zone  doesn't

00:16:22.048 --> 00:16:22.848 align:middle line:90%
feel dated.

00:16:22.848 --> 00:16:23.916 align:middle line:90%
You watch those episodes...

00:16:23.916 --> 00:16:25.317 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: Oh,
timeless, timeless.

00:16:25.317 --> 00:16:26.819 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: Well, I mean, an
old woman who's afraid of death.

00:16:26.819 --> 00:16:28.587 align:middle line:84%
I mean, that's going
to be with us forever.

00:16:28.587 --> 00:16:30.756 align:middle line:84%
We're all -- we're all afraid
of death one way or another.

00:16:30.756 --> 00:16:32.758 align:middle line:84%
And so these are issues
that are with us --

00:16:32.758 --> 00:16:34.960 align:middle line:84%
the issues of life and
death, and meaning,

00:16:34.960 --> 00:16:36.328 align:middle line:90%
and finding a meaningful life.

00:16:36.328 --> 00:16:39.698 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you couldn't choose
subjects more -- more important.

00:16:39.698 --> 00:16:41.333 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: Two great
actors who are no longer

00:16:41.333 --> 00:16:44.303 align:middle line:84%
with us, Jack Klugman
and Jonathan Winters...

00:16:44.303 --> 00:16:45.671 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yeah.

00:16:45.671 --> 00:16:46.939 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: "A Game of
Pool," what's that all about?

00:16:46.939 --> 00:16:48.307 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: Well, it's
a great piece of writing.

00:16:48.307 --> 00:16:49.708 align:middle line:84%
And you know many of these
Twilight Zone  episodes take

00:16:49.708 --> 00:16:53.079 align:middle line:84%
place in one room or just a few
rooms, beautifully contained.

00:16:53.079 --> 00:16:56.348 align:middle line:84%
And this is about a pool player
who wants to be the best,

00:16:56.348 --> 00:16:58.217 align:middle line:84%
but the best pool
player ever has died,

00:16:58.217 --> 00:17:00.653 align:middle line:84%
and so he challenges this
pool player to come back

00:17:00.653 --> 00:17:02.655 align:middle line:84%
from the other side
to play a game of pool

00:17:02.655 --> 00:17:05.291 align:middle line:84%
with very high stakes,
life and death.

00:17:05.291 --> 00:17:06.558 align:middle line:84%
And Jack Klugman
of course was one

00:17:06.558 --> 00:17:07.793 align:middle line:90%
of Serling's favorite actors.

00:17:07.793 --> 00:17:09.128 align:middle line:84%
He was in a number of
Twilight Zone  episodes,

00:17:09.128 --> 00:17:10.930 align:middle line:84%
four  Twilight Zone
episodes, in fact.

00:17:10.930 --> 00:17:13.265 align:middle line:84%
Brilliant actor, and this
is before  The Odd Couple ,

00:17:13.265 --> 00:17:14.533 align:middle line:84%
before a lot of things
that broadened...

00:17:14.533 --> 00:17:15.868 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: This was
before he was a superstar.

00:17:15.868 --> 00:17:16.568 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes.

00:17:16.568 --> 00:17:17.870 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Right?

00:17:17.870 --> 00:17:19.105 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: Definitely,
and then Jonathan Winters,

00:17:19.105 --> 00:17:19.805 align:middle line:84%
it's fascinating because
George Clayton Johnson wrote

00:17:19.805 --> 00:17:21.172 align:middle line:90%
that script, and in --

00:17:21.172 --> 00:17:24.410 align:middle line:84%
in the description in the script
he was envisioning Burl Ives

00:17:24.410 --> 00:17:25.211 align:middle line:90%
to play the fat...

00:17:25.211 --> 00:17:26.211 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Hmm-mm.

00:17:26.211 --> 00:17:27.513 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: ...the
fat pool player.

00:17:27.513 --> 00:17:29.715 align:middle line:84%
But  Twilight Zone  like
often to cast against type.

00:17:29.715 --> 00:17:30.850 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Yeah.

00:17:30.850 --> 00:17:31.984 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: And they
cast numerous comedians

00:17:31.984 --> 00:17:34.186 align:middle line:84%
in serious roles, and
Jonathan Winters was one

00:17:34.186 --> 00:17:35.287 align:middle line:84%
of the top comedians
of the time,

00:17:35.287 --> 00:17:36.222 align:middle line:90%
and interestingly enough...

00:17:36.222 --> 00:17:37.056 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
He did a good job.

00:17:37.056 --> 00:17:38.257 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Well, he had --

00:17:38.257 --> 00:17:39.024 align:middle line:84%
Jonathan Winters had just
had a nervous breakdown,

00:17:39.024 --> 00:17:39.925 align:middle line:90%
and this was the first...

00:17:39.925 --> 00:17:41.160 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Oh, really?

00:17:41.160 --> 00:17:42.361 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: This was
the first acting role he did

00:17:42.361 --> 00:17:44.430 align:middle line:84%
after coming out of the
-- the mental institution.

00:17:44.430 --> 00:17:47.199 align:middle line:84%
And -- and Buzz Kulik was the
director, a very solid director

00:17:47.199 --> 00:17:49.902 align:middle line:84%
of drama, and he and Jonathan
Winters talked very, very,

00:17:49.902 --> 00:17:51.670 align:middle line:84%
you know, intently about
how to do the role.

00:17:51.670 --> 00:17:52.838 align:middle line:84%
And Winters was a
little nervous,

00:17:52.838 --> 00:17:54.807 align:middle line:84%
but he really --
really nailed it.

00:17:54.807 --> 00:17:55.841 align:middle line:90%
He did a great job.

00:17:55.841 --> 00:17:57.376 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: Well
let's take a look.

00:17:57.376 --> 00:17:59.512 align:middle line:90%
>> Then what?

00:17:59.512 --> 00:18:03.549 align:middle line:84%
>> Something to make my
long journey worthwhile.

00:18:03.549 --> 00:18:05.551 align:middle line:90%
>> Name it.

00:18:05.551 --> 00:18:09.155 align:middle line:84%
>> You said you'd give
anything for a game with me.

00:18:09.155 --> 00:18:10.222 align:middle line:90%
Anything?

00:18:10.222 --> 00:18:14.727 align:middle line:84%
>> What are you talking
about, Mister?

00:18:14.727 --> 00:18:18.764 align:middle line:84%
Just what kind of stakes
are you talking about?

00:18:18.764 --> 00:18:21.600 align:middle line:90%
>> Life or death.

00:18:21.600 --> 00:18:23.936 align:middle line:90%
You beat me, and you live.

00:18:23.936 --> 00:18:27.373 align:middle line:84%
You lose, and you die
[Background Music].

00:18:27.373 --> 00:18:28.941 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: Those
are high stakes, Marc.

00:18:28.941 --> 00:18:29.909 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes,
they are, indeed.

00:18:29.909 --> 00:18:31.243 align:middle line:90%
They are, indeed.

00:18:31.243 --> 00:18:33.813 align:middle line:84%
And -- but again, these --
these two actors are so present

00:18:33.813 --> 00:18:36.148 align:middle line:84%
to the material, and -- and
Jack Klugman just anchors it.

00:18:36.148 --> 00:18:38.184 align:middle line:84%
And he -- Jack Klugman's
so great

00:18:38.184 --> 00:18:41.554 align:middle line:84%
at playing longing
and intensity.

00:18:41.554 --> 00:18:44.056 align:middle line:84%
And -- and, you know,  Twilight
Zone  often brought the best

00:18:44.056 --> 00:18:46.025 align:middle line:84%
performances in many of these
actors because as much as I

00:18:46.025 --> 00:18:48.127 align:middle line:84%
like Jack Klugman
in  The Odd Couple

00:18:48.127 --> 00:18:49.628 align:middle line:90%
and later as Quincy you know...

00:18:49.628 --> 00:18:50.763 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Right.

00:18:50.763 --> 00:18:52.164 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: You know
his best work really is

00:18:52.164 --> 00:18:54.533 align:middle line:84%
in  Twilight Zone , and if
you look at this or in "Praise

00:18:54.533 --> 00:18:56.435 align:middle line:84%
of Pip," or "Passage for
Trumpet," or "Death Ship,"

00:18:56.435 --> 00:18:58.904 align:middle line:84%
another episode he
did, he's phenomenal.

00:18:58.904 --> 00:19:00.039 align:middle line:90%
He's phenomenal.

00:19:00.039 --> 00:19:02.241 align:middle line:84%
And I remember in one
of Rod's scripts in --

00:19:02.241 --> 00:19:04.310 align:middle line:84%
in "Passage for Trumpet,"
the first  Twilight Zone

00:19:04.310 --> 00:19:07.413 align:middle line:84%
that Jack Klugman did, there's
a moment where Rod says --

00:19:07.413 --> 00:19:10.282 align:middle line:84%
Jack Klugman's character's
talking to this girl,

00:19:10.282 --> 00:19:12.084 align:middle line:84%
and he's a lonely man,
and there's a possibility

00:19:12.084 --> 00:19:15.154 align:middle line:84%
of a relationship, and -- and
Rod wrote, "His face lights

00:19:15.154 --> 00:19:17.089 align:middle line:90%
up like 1,000-watt bulb."

00:19:17.089 --> 00:19:18.958 align:middle line:84%
And Jack Klugman --
Klugman just does that.

00:19:18.958 --> 00:19:20.092 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: You
were telling me once

00:19:20.092 --> 00:19:22.194 align:middle line:84%
that you were rummaging
around Serling's attic.

00:19:22.194 --> 00:19:23.395 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes!

00:19:23.395 --> 00:19:24.263 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: His wife
Carol said, "Go on up,

00:19:24.263 --> 00:19:25.231 align:middle line:90%
and do what you have to do."

00:19:25.231 --> 00:19:26.332 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: That's right.

00:19:26.332 --> 00:19:27.233 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: You
found some episodes...

00:19:27.233 --> 00:19:28.367 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: That's right.

00:19:28.367 --> 00:19:29.335 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: ...that
were never put to film.

00:19:29.335 --> 00:19:30.669 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: That's right.

00:19:30.669 --> 00:19:31.370 align:middle line:84%
Well, I started writing  The
Twilight Zone Companion

00:19:31.370 --> 00:19:32.438 align:middle line:90%
when I was 22 years old.

00:19:32.438 --> 00:19:33.639 align:middle line:84%
I was right out --
right out of college.

00:19:33.639 --> 00:19:35.474 align:middle line:84%
It was two years
after Rod's death.

00:19:35.474 --> 00:19:37.009 align:middle line:90%
He died very early at 50...

00:19:37.009 --> 00:19:37.843 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Yes.

00:19:37.843 --> 00:19:38.811 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: ...as you know.

00:19:38.811 --> 00:19:40.212 align:middle line:84%
And so I approached
Carol Serling.

00:19:40.212 --> 00:19:41.614 align:middle line:84%
I'd already been interviewing
a number of people who'd worked

00:19:41.614 --> 00:19:45.417 align:middle line:84%
on the show, and -- and she gave
me full access to everything.

00:19:45.417 --> 00:19:47.853 align:middle line:84%
So Rod -- Rod's scripts
and scrapbooks were up --

00:19:47.853 --> 00:19:50.122 align:middle line:84%
were up in the attic of this
big house in Pacific Palisades,

00:19:50.122 --> 00:19:51.390 align:middle line:90%
so I was literally crawling

00:19:51.390 --> 00:19:53.826 align:middle line:84%
through Rod's attic,
and I found this box.

00:19:53.826 --> 00:19:55.995 align:middle line:84%
And it was an unmarked
box, and I opened it up,

00:19:55.995 --> 00:19:57.229 align:middle line:84%
and there were  Twilight
Zone  scripts

00:19:57.229 --> 00:19:58.797 align:middle line:84%
that were written
but never made.

00:19:58.797 --> 00:20:01.467 align:middle line:84%
There were two by Ray Bradbury;
there were several by Serling;

00:20:01.467 --> 00:20:03.936 align:middle line:84%
several by Charles
Beaumont and Matheson.

00:20:03.936 --> 00:20:05.604 align:middle line:84%
And it was just a treasure
trove; it was amazing,

00:20:05.604 --> 00:20:07.006 align:middle line:90%
phenomenal -- phenomenal stuff.

00:20:07.006 --> 00:20:09.174 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: Let's go back
to our  Beyond Belief  cam

00:20:09.174 --> 00:20:11.844 align:middle line:84%
and take another
question for Marc Zicree.

00:20:11.844 --> 00:20:12.945 align:middle line:90%
>> Hi, Marc.

00:20:12.945 --> 00:20:14.546 align:middle line:90%
I'm David from Austin.

00:20:14.546 --> 00:20:16.849 align:middle line:84%
I've always wondered, who
was the voice of the doll

00:20:16.849 --> 00:20:19.618 align:middle line:84%
in the  Twilight Zone
episode "Living Doll"?

00:20:19.618 --> 00:20:21.220 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: June
Foray, who was the voice

00:20:21.220 --> 00:20:24.290 align:middle line:84%
of Rocky the Flying Squirrel,
is the voice of Talky Tina.

00:20:24.290 --> 00:20:27.159 align:middle line:84%
But interestingly enough she was
also the voice of Chatty Cathy,

00:20:27.159 --> 00:20:28.494 align:middle line:90%
which was the very popular...

00:20:28.494 --> 00:20:29.461 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Oh, sure.

00:20:29.461 --> 00:20:30.396 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: ...doll
at the time.

00:20:30.396 --> 00:20:31.230 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
Pull thing, yeah.

00:20:31.230 --> 00:20:32.598 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: That's right.

00:20:32.598 --> 00:20:33.299 align:middle line:84%
"The Living Doll" is basically
doing a -- doing a riff on.

00:20:33.299 --> 00:20:34.533 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Yeah.

00:20:34.533 --> 00:20:35.200 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: And so she's
just absolutely perfect;

00:20:35.200 --> 00:20:36.368 align:middle line:90%
couldn't be better.

00:20:36.368 --> 00:20:37.469 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: You
know the great story

00:20:37.469 --> 00:20:39.972 align:middle line:90%
of my little granddaughter Mia.

00:20:39.972 --> 00:20:46.245 align:middle line:84%
I bought her that little doll,
and it's a scary little doll.

00:20:46.245 --> 00:20:48.047 align:middle line:90%
It -- it really is.

00:20:48.047 --> 00:20:50.416 align:middle line:84%
And my -- my daughter,
her mother,

00:20:50.416 --> 00:20:52.351 align:middle line:90%
had it put on her counter.

00:20:52.351 --> 00:20:53.419 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Hmm-mm.

00:20:53.419 --> 00:20:54.119 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: And
so she would see it

00:20:54.119 --> 00:20:55.688 align:middle line:90%
when she went to bed.

00:20:55.688 --> 00:20:59.224 align:middle line:84%
And she'd look at it and
go, "Mom, put it back."

00:20:59.224 --> 00:21:01.493 align:middle line:84%
So she'd have to
literally take that doll...

00:21:01.493 --> 00:21:02.861 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes.

00:21:02.861 --> 00:21:03.862 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: ...and put
it in just -- and cover it up.

00:21:03.862 --> 00:21:05.230 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Wow.

00:21:05.230 --> 00:21:06.632 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: She -- she
wanted nothing to do with that.

00:21:06.632 --> 00:21:08.500 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: Yeah, well
you know  Twilight Zone  goes

00:21:08.500 --> 00:21:09.868 align:middle line:90%
to some pretty dark places.

00:21:09.868 --> 00:21:12.905 align:middle line:84%
And -- and it's funny because
Rod did not even let his own

00:21:12.905 --> 00:21:14.340 align:middle line:84%
children watch  The
Twilight Zone

00:21:14.340 --> 00:21:15.808 align:middle line:90%
when it was on the network.

00:21:15.808 --> 00:21:18.711 align:middle line:84%
And Anne Serling told me
that one time she crept

00:21:18.711 --> 00:21:21.313 align:middle line:84%
down past her bedtime and
looked through the bannister,

00:21:21.313 --> 00:21:22.815 align:middle line:84%
and her parents were
watching one of the episodes

00:21:22.815 --> 00:21:25.250 align:middle line:84%
of  Twilight Zone ; it was
"Nightmare at 20,000 Feet,"

00:21:25.250 --> 00:21:26.885 align:middle line:84%
and the one with the
gremlin on the wing.

00:21:26.885 --> 00:21:29.355 align:middle line:84%
And -- and it scared her
to death, and she thought,

00:21:29.355 --> 00:21:32.191 align:middle line:84%
"This is what my daddy does
for a living [laughter]?"

00:21:32.191 --> 00:21:34.326 align:middle line:90%
So -- so it was -- but yeah.

00:21:34.326 --> 00:21:35.594 align:middle line:84%
They're -- they're
indelible images.

00:21:35.594 --> 00:21:37.196 align:middle line:84%
There's -- they just --
they stay with you forever.

00:21:37.196 --> 00:21:39.865 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: How popular
was the show in the ratings?

00:21:39.865 --> 00:21:42.134 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: It -- well, the
funny thing is it was popular,

00:21:42.134 --> 00:21:43.769 align:middle line:90%
but it wasn't a top-rated show.

00:21:43.769 --> 00:21:46.338 align:middle line:84%
But the fascinating thing is
compared to the audiences now,

00:21:46.338 --> 00:21:48.307 align:middle line:84%
you know a show now
on the network on CBS

00:21:48.307 --> 00:21:51.643 align:middle line:84%
if they get 10 million
viewers that's a huge hit.

00:21:51.643 --> 00:21:53.078 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Yeah.

00:21:53.078 --> 00:21:53.612 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree:  The Twilight
Zone  was getting 40 million,

00:21:53.612 --> 00:21:54.313 align:middle line:90%
and that...

00:21:54.313 --> 00:21:55.013 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Whoa!

00:21:55.013 --> 00:21:56.348 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yeah.

00:21:56.348 --> 00:21:57.683 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: Of course,
you only had three networks.

00:21:57.683 --> 00:21:58.884 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: There were
only three networks, exactly.

00:21:58.884 --> 00:22:00.018 align:middle line:84%
And -- and of course this
was before home videos,

00:22:00.018 --> 00:22:01.220 align:middle line:84%
so you couldn't record a
show and watch it later.

00:22:01.220 --> 00:22:02.521 align:middle line:84%
It was on when it was
on, and you watched it.

00:22:02.521 --> 00:22:03.522 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
You had to watch it.

00:22:03.522 --> 00:22:04.590 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: Yeah,
and I remember

00:22:04.590 --> 00:22:05.858 align:middle line:84%
when the original
Star Trek  was on.

00:22:05.858 --> 00:22:08.427 align:middle line:84%
I was a kid, and I
recorded them on audio --

00:22:08.427 --> 00:22:09.862 align:middle line:84%
reel-to-reel audiotape
just in case...

00:22:09.862 --> 00:22:11.163 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
Could hear them.

00:22:11.163 --> 00:22:11.864 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: ...just in
case it never showed again.

00:22:11.864 --> 00:22:13.232 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Yeah.

00:22:13.232 --> 00:22:14.400 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: And so it's a
very different world we live

00:22:14.400 --> 00:22:15.234 align:middle line:90%
in now.

00:22:15.234 --> 00:22:15.801 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Yeah, it is.

00:22:15.801 --> 00:22:16.835 align:middle line:90%
It's dramatic.

00:22:16.835 --> 00:22:19.571 align:middle line:84%
And when it ended
-- it was on CBS.

00:22:19.571 --> 00:22:20.272 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes.

00:22:20.272 --> 00:22:20.973 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: Right?

00:22:20.973 --> 00:22:21.907 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yeah.

00:22:21.907 --> 00:22:22.941 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
Was Serling upset?

00:22:22.941 --> 00:22:24.276 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: He
had mixed emotions.

00:22:24.276 --> 00:22:25.878 align:middle line:84%
He had written so much over
those years, and also during

00:22:25.878 --> 00:22:27.980 align:middle line:84%
that time he wrote  Seven
Days in May  the movie.

00:22:27.980 --> 00:22:31.283 align:middle line:84%
He was writing movies; he
was writing books, as well.

00:22:31.283 --> 00:22:34.453 align:middle line:84%
So he was very tired, but -- but
also I think he was a little sad

00:22:34.453 --> 00:22:36.522 align:middle line:84%
that it was canceled,
so he went to ABC,

00:22:36.522 --> 00:22:39.124 align:middle line:84%
pitched a show called  Rod
Serling's Wax Museum ,

00:22:39.124 --> 00:22:41.527 align:middle line:84%
and it would have been Rod
in a spooky mansion on --

00:22:41.527 --> 00:22:43.362 align:middle line:84%
on an island, and
you would go in,

00:22:43.362 --> 00:22:44.696 align:middle line:84%
and you would see
these wax figures.

00:22:44.696 --> 00:22:46.265 align:middle line:84%
They would all have
hoods over their heads,

00:22:46.265 --> 00:22:48.767 align:middle line:84%
and then he would pull the
hood off, and you'd see the --

00:22:48.767 --> 00:22:50.736 align:middle line:84%
a wax figure of that
week's actor,

00:22:50.736 --> 00:22:52.504 align:middle line:84%
and then he would tell the
story, and then you'd go

00:22:52.504 --> 00:22:53.572 align:middle line:90%
into the dramatization.

00:22:53.572 --> 00:22:54.673 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
Ah, interesting.

00:22:54.673 --> 00:22:56.074 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: And
-- and that didn't --

00:22:56.074 --> 00:22:58.177 align:middle line:84%
and he also had done a book
called  Rod Serling's Triple W,"

00:22:58.177 --> 00:23:00.112 align:middle line:84%
which is witches,
werewolves, and warlocks.

00:23:00.112 --> 00:23:02.281 align:middle line:84%
And so they talked about
several different ideas, but --

00:23:02.281 --> 00:23:04.016 align:middle line:84%
but it was very clear to
Rod very quickly that --

00:23:04.016 --> 00:23:05.484 align:middle line:84%
that the head of ABC
just wanted to have sort

00:23:05.484 --> 00:23:08.053 align:middle line:84%
of a spook show, and nothing
that would have any meaning,

00:23:08.053 --> 00:23:10.255 align:middle line:84%
and so he went to the press
and just said, "Well, you know,

00:23:10.255 --> 00:23:11.390 align:middle line:90%
this isn't going to work."

00:23:11.390 --> 00:23:13.559 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: It's
not going to work.

00:23:13.559 --> 00:23:14.526 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: No.

00:23:14.526 --> 00:23:15.794 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
And he was done.

00:23:15.794 --> 00:23:18.363 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: So I think
he felt very melancholy

00:23:18.363 --> 00:23:19.665 align:middle line:84%
about it being over,
and then he --

00:23:19.665 --> 00:23:22.000 align:middle line:84%
as you said, he tried to
get something going again

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:25.137 align:middle line:84%
with Night Gallery , but
he didn't have the control

00:23:25.137 --> 00:23:27.439 align:middle line:84%
with  Night Gallery , so
there are a few episodes,

00:23:27.439 --> 00:23:30.008 align:middle line:84%
like the "Tearing
Down Tim Riley's Bar"

00:23:30.008 --> 00:23:32.344 align:middle line:84%
that are very moving,
very touching, but --

00:23:32.344 --> 00:23:34.346 align:middle line:84%
but he was not happy
with  Night Gallery .

00:23:34.346 --> 00:23:37.316 align:middle line:84%
It wasn't his baby like
Twilight Zone  was.

00:23:37.316 --> 00:23:39.451 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: One of
our friends, Billy Mumy...

00:23:39.451 --> 00:23:40.385 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes.

00:23:40.385 --> 00:23:41.420 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
Billy, of course,

00:23:41.420 --> 00:23:42.121 align:middle line:84%
in a couple  Twilight
Zone  episodes.

00:23:42.121 --> 00:23:43.055 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes.

00:23:43.055 --> 00:23:43.956 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory:
And of course was

00:23:43.956 --> 00:23:44.656 align:middle line:90%
in  Lost in Space  [laughter].

00:23:44.656 --> 00:23:45.991 align:middle line:90%
He was Will Robinson.

00:23:45.991 --> 00:23:46.658 align:middle line:90%
Great guy.

00:23:46.658 --> 00:23:48.060 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes.

00:23:48.060 --> 00:23:49.027 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: Musician now,
and just one heck of a person,

00:23:49.027 --> 00:23:49.962 align:middle line:84%
but he was in "It's
a Good Life"...

00:23:49.962 --> 00:23:51.163 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes.

00:23:51.163 --> 00:23:51.830 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: ...where
everybody hated him...

00:23:51.830 --> 00:23:53.031 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Yes.

00:23:53.031 --> 00:23:53.732 align:middle line:84%
>> George Noory: ...as
the little kid [laughter].

00:23:53.732 --> 00:23:54.733 align:middle line:90%
Do you remember that?

00:23:54.733 --> 00:23:55.634 align:middle line:84%
>> Marc Zicree: I
remember it well.

00:23:55.634 --> 00:23:57.402 align:middle line:90%
You bet. It's a great episode.

00:23:57.402 --> 00:24:00.072 align:middle line:84%
It's based on a short
story by Jerome Bixby,

00:24:00.072 --> 00:24:02.574 align:middle line:84%
one of the classic short
stories of science fiction.

00:24:02.574 --> 00:24:03.909 align:middle line:90%
Rod adapted it.

00:24:03.909 --> 00:24:06.178 align:middle line:84%
He wrote that script in eight
hours, that entire script.

00:24:06.178 --> 00:24:06.879 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: That was it?

00:24:06.879 --> 00:24:08.113 align:middle line:90%
>> Marc Zicree: Hmm-mm.

00:24:08.113 --> 00:24:09.748 align:middle line:84%
And  Twilight Zone  was
shot in three days' time.

00:24:09.748 --> 00:24:11.650 align:middle line:84%
There was one day of
rehearsal, and then three days,

00:24:11.650 --> 00:24:12.985 align:middle line:90%
and then you were done.

00:24:12.985 --> 00:24:16.388 align:middle line:84%
So it's astonishing; these
classics were made so quickly.

00:24:16.388 --> 00:24:18.156 align:middle line:90%
And it's just a superb episode.

00:24:18.156 --> 00:24:19.591 align:middle line:90%
It's a great ensemble piece.

00:24:19.591 --> 00:24:20.959 align:middle line:84%
Cloris Leachman is
terrific in it, John Larch,

00:24:20.959 --> 00:24:21.994 align:middle line:90%
and Billy Mumy is phenomenal.

00:24:21.994 --> 00:24:22.828 align:middle line:84%
Just astonishing;
scary, really scary.

00:24:22.828 --> 00:24:24.229 align:middle line:90%
>> George Noory: He really is.

00:24:24.229 --> 00:24:25.297 align:middle line:84%
Let's take a little look at this
clip from "It's a Good Life."

